liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Chair Gleeson is questioning Professor Cole. Asked whether there was any chance of changing his position once airborne, he says that based on the numbers and research, it's difficult to conclusively say Maynard would have been able to make a conscious decision. A minute later, he uses a memorable line to describe human momentum in mid-air. "Once he's in flight he's basically a projectile ... a frisbee with legs".
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 'Once he's in flight, he's basically a projectile': Professor Cole talks about the mechanics

children.content: Chair Gleeson is questioning Professor Cole.

Asked whether there was any chance of changing his position once airborne, he says that based on the numbers and research, it's difficult to conclusively say Maynard would have been able to make a conscious decision.
A minute later, he uses a memorable line to describe human momentum in mid-air.
"Once he's in flight he's basically a projectile ... a frisbee with legs".

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Professor Michael Cole who is from the Australian Catholic University, has made an expert report for the case. He was asked eight questions in writing and responded in kind. He says he stands by his answers Woods asks him about his answer to what opportunity there was for Maynard to avoid the collision once he left the ground. The answer was that he had no opportunity to avoid the collision. "That means if he was to avoid the collision he needed to do so before he left the ground," Woods suggests. "Yes, he'd have to make that even before he initiated the motor sequence to leave the ground," Professor Cole replies. He adds that that sequence includes squatting and bending his knees to get ready to propel himself up. "Based on the numbers and research, it's difficult to conclusively say Maynard would've been able to make any conscious decision to reposition his body," Professor Cole says.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Biomechanist Professor Michael Cole to give evidence

children.content: Professor Michael Cole who is from the Australian Catholic University, has made an expert report for the case.
He was asked eight questions in writing and responded in kind.
He says he stands by his answers
Woods asks him about his answer to what opportunity there was for Maynard to avoid the collision once he left the ground. The answer was that he had no opportunity to avoid the collision.
"That means if he was to avoid the collision he needed to do so before he left the ground," Woods suggests.
"Yes, he'd have to make that even before he initiated the motor sequence to leave the ground," Professor Cole replies.
He adds that that sequence includes squatting and bending his knees to get ready to propel himself up.
"Based on the numbers and research, it's difficult to conclusively say Maynard would've been able to make any conscious decision to reposition his body," Professor Cole says.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Woods gets the hearing to forward the footage of the incident to the point where Brayshaw has got the ball and is getting ready to kick. He is looking down. "The forward momentum (of Maynard) is very much pronounced," Woods says. He continues, saying that while the original decision was to attempt a spoil, that once he leaves the ground, he puts himself in a position "where a possible or even likely outcome is rough conduct". They forward the footage, and Woods says "the look of shock on Brayshaw's face" showed that he was completely surprised by what was about to happen.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Woods goes to the footage to say it was unreasonable for Maynard to jump to spoil
